      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is not required at MRL 2. The simulation team follows internal SOPs for boundary condition setup and post-processing, providing informal protection against use error without formal assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form selection justified by literature precedent and scope of intended use; turbulence model appropriate for rotating machinery hemolysis prediction.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence closure selected based on published benchmark studies for centrifugal blood pumps demonstrating superior near-wall shear stress accuracy relative to k-epsilon variants. Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model selected as the industry-standard formulation for regulatory submissions. The model derivation explicitly assumes that cumulative red blood cell damage is a linear function of shear stress exposure time integrated along individual pathlines — i.e., damage contributions are independently additive. This assumption is stated as a theoretical precondition for valid model application. The package does not include a validation result or sensitivity analysis confirming that this linear superposition condition is satisfied across all five COU operating points, particularly the higher-speed, higher-shear conditions at 5000 RPM where erythrocyte viscoelastic memory effects may introduce non-linear damage accumulation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties and boundary conditions documented with uncertainty ranges; sensitivity of NIH to input variability quantified.",
      "rationale": "Blood analog density (1056 kg/m³ ± 0.5%), dynamic viscosity (0.0035 Pa·s ± 3%), and inlet flow waveform characterized. One-at-a-time sensitivity study shows NIH sensitivity to viscosity is 0.8 (NIH changes 0.8% per 1% viscosity change), confirming low parametric sensitivity. Rotational speed uncertainty ±0.5% contributes NIH uncertainty of ±1.2%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
